<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_gauss_factorization" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Factorization in Gaussian integers</title>
<subsection xml:id="ss_division_alg">
<title>Division and Euclidean algorithms</title>
<theorem xml:id="th_div_alg_gauss">
<title>Division algorithm in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> be Gaussian integers with <m>\beta\ne 0</m>. There are Gaussian integers <m>q,r\in \Z[i]</m> satisfying the following conditions. 
<ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=q\beta+r</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>0\leq N(r)&lt; N(\beta)</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
Moreover, <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> can be produced via the following procedure.  
<ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find <m>\gamma\in \Q[i]</m> satisfying <m>\gamma\beta=\alpha</m>: <ie/>, set <m>\gamma=\beta^{-1}\alpha</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Write <m>\gamma=q+(s+ti)</m>, where <m>q\in \Z[i]</m> and <m>\{\abs{s},\abs{t}\}\subseteq [0,1/2]</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We have <m>\alpha=q\beta+r</m>, where <m>r=\alpha-q\beta</m> satisfies <m>0\leq N(r)&lt; N(\beta)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    That the procedure above produces a <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> in <m>\Z[i]</m> satisfying <m>\alpha=q\beta+r</m> is clear. It remains only to show that <m>0\leq N(r)&lt; N(\beta)</m>. We have 
    <md>
        <mrow>N(r) \amp =N(\alpha-q\beta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = N(\gamma\beta-q\beta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =N(\gamma-q)N(\beta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =N(s+ti)N(\beta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =(s^2+t^2)N(\beta)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; N(\beta) \amp (s^2+t^2\leq \tfrac{1}{4}+\tfrac{1}{4}=\tfrac{1}{2})</mrow>
    </md>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<example xml:id="eg_div_alg_gauss">
<title>Division algorithm in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
For the given <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>, find <m>q,r\in \Z[i]</m> satisfying <m>\alpha=q\beta+r</m> and <m>0\leq N(r)&lt; N(\beta)</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=2+7i</m>, <m>\beta=1+2i</m> 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=5-5i</m>, <m>\beta=2-4i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
    In both cases we follow the procedure described in <xref ref="th_div_alg_gauss"/>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Set 
            <md>
                \gamma=\beta^{-1}\alpha=\frac{1}{5}(1-2i)(2+7i)=\frac{16}{5}+\frac{3}{5}i
            </md>.
            We pick <m>q</m> to be a closest Gaussian integer to this element of <m>\C</m>. In this case we can pick <m>q=3+i</m>, in which case 
            <md>
                <mrow>r \amp = \alpha-q\beta</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 2+7i-(3+i)(1+2i)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =2+7i-(1+7i)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =1</mrow>
            </md>.
            Thus our instance of the division algorithm in this case is 
            <md>
                2+7i=(3+i)(1+2i)+1
            </md>.
            Note that we have <m>N(1)=1&lt; N(\beta)=5</m>, as stipulated.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have 
            <md>
                \gamma=\beta^{-1}\alpha=\frac{1}{20}(2+4i)(5-5i)=\frac{3}{2}-\frac{1}{2}i
            </md>.
            In this case, since <m>\gamma</m> lies in the center of the Gaussian square with vertices <m>1</m>, <m>2</m>, <m>1-i</m>, and <m>2-i</m>, any one of those vertices can serve as our <m>q</m>!
        </p>
        <p>
            Clearly, <m>q=1</m> is the easiest to deal with, resulting in <m>r=\alpha-1\beta=3+i</m> and a division algorithm statement of 
            <md>
                5-5i=1\cdot (2-4i)+(3+i), \ N(3+i)=10&lt; N(2-4i)=20
            </md>.
            Let see what happens for another choice of <m>q</m>. Taking <m>q=1-i</m>, we have 
            <md>
                r=\alpha-(1-i)\beta=5-5i-(3-6i)=2+i
            </md>
            and our division algorithm statement is 
            <md>
                5-5i=(1-i)(2-4i)+(2+i), \ N(2+i)=5&lt; N(2-4i)=20
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</example>

    <definition xml:id="d_gcd_lcm">
    <title>Greatest common divisor and least common multiple</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a subring of <m>\C</m>. Given elements <m>\alpha, \beta\in R</m> a <term>greatest common divisor</term> (or <term>GCD</term>) of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> is an element <m>\delta\in R</m> satisfying the following conditions: 
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\delta\mid \alpha</m> and <m>\delta\mid \beta</m>;
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                if <m>\delta'\in R</m> satisfies <m>\delta'\mid \alpha</m> and <m>\delta'\mid \beta</m>, then <m>\delta'\mid \delta</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
    A <term>least common multiple</term> (or <term>LCM</term>) of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> is an element <m>\mu\in R</m> satisfying the following conditions:
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\alpha\mid \mu</m> and <m>\beta\mid \mu</m>;
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                if <m>\mu'\in R</m> satisfies <m>\alpha\mid \mu'</m> and <m>\beta\mid \mu'</m>, then <m>\mu\mid \mu'</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    More generally, a greatest common divisor of elements <m>\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n</m> of <m>R</m> is an element <m>\delta\in R</m> such that <m>\delta\mid \alpha_i</m> for all <m>i</m>, and if <m>\delta'\in R</m> satisfies <m>\delta'\mid \alpha_i</m> for all <m>i</m>, then <m>\delta'\mid \delta</m>. Lastly, we say that elements <m>\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n</m> are <term>relatively prime</term> if they have <m>1</m> as a GCD. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
        <title>GCDs and LCDs</title>
        <p>
            Although the definition of GCDs and LCMs is a straightforward generalization of the corresponding notion from the integers, you should proceed with caution when making use of these concepts. In particular, be aware of the following facts: 
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        GCDs and LCMs need not exist in an arbitrary subring of <m>\C</m>; 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        if GCDs and LCMs do exist, they are only unique modulo multiplication by a unit. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        The uniqueness issue is already in evidence in the context of the integers. To nonzero integers <m>a, b</m> will always have two GCDs, namely <m>\gcd(a,b)</m> and <m>-\gcd(a,b)</m>, where <m>\gcd(a,b)</m>, as you will recall, is defined to be the greatest <em>positive</em> integer dividing <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.  
        </p>
    </remark>


<theorem xml:id="th_euc_alg">
    <title>Euclidean algorithm in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
       Given elements <m>\alpha,\beta\in \Z[i]</m>, one of which is nonzero, we can produce a GCD following the Euclidean algorithm below.
    </p>
    <p>
        If <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>, then <m>\alpha</m> is a GCD of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>.  Otherwise,  we can produce a sequence of division algorithm instances 
            <md number="no">
                        <mrow>\beta\amp =q_1\alpha+r_1 \amp r_1\amp \ne 0, N(r_1)&lt; N(\alpha) </mrow>
                        <mrow>\alpha\amp =q_2r_1+r_2 \amp r_2\amp \ne 0, N(r_2)&lt; N(r_1)</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp \vdots</mrow>
                        <mrow>r_{n-1} \amp =q_{n+1}r_{n}+r_{n+1} \amp r_{n+1}\amp\ne 0, N(r_{n+1})&lt; N(r_{n})</mrow>
                        <mrow>r_{n} \amp = q_{n+2}r_{n+1}+\boxed{0}</mrow>
                    </md>,
                and it follows that <m>r_{n+1}</m> is a GCD of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>.
                Moreover, beginning with the penultimate equation <m>r_{n-1}=q_{n+1}r_n+r_{n+1}</m>, and working our way upward, solving successively for <m>r_{k}</m> in terms of <m>r_{k-1}</m> and <m>r_{k-2}</m>, we can find elements <m>\gamma, \delta\in R</m> satisfying 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>r_{n+1} \amp =\gamma\alpha+\delta\beta</mrow> 
                    </md>.
                </p>
           
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        First note that if <m>\beta=q\alpha+r</m> for some <m>q,r\in \Z[i]</m>, then <m>\delta</m> is a GCD of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> if and only if it is a GCD of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>r</m>, using the usual divisibility arguments.  
    </p>
    <p>
        It follows by induction that if we have a sequence of division algorithm instances as in (2), then <m>\delta</m> is a GCD of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> if and only if it is a GCD of <m></m>
        It suffices, then, to show that there is such a sequence. The basic idea is that at each step 
        <md>
            <mrow>r_{k} \amp =q_{k+2}r_{k+1}+r_{k+2}</mrow>
        </md>,
        if <m>r_{k+2}\ne 0</m>, then we can apply the division algorithm to <m>r_{k+2}</m> and <m>r_{k+1}</m>. Since at each step where the remainder is nonzero, the successive remainder has strictly smaller <m>N</m>-value, the process must terminate: <ie/>, at some point we must have <m>r_{k}=0</m>. 
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <example xml:id="eg_gauss_ints">
<title>GCD in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Find a GCD <m>\delta</m> of <m>2</m> and <m>1+3i</m> in <m>\Z[i]</m>, and write <m>\delta=2\alpha+(1+3i)\beta</m> for some <m>\alpha, \beta\in \Z[i]</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Noting that <m>N(2)=4</m> and <m>N(1+3i)=10</m>, we start the Euclidean algorithm by dividing <m>1+3i</m> by <m>2</m>. 
<md>
    <mrow>1+3i \amp =(1+i)2+(-1+i)</mrow>
    <mrow>2 \amp =(-1+i)(-1-i)+\boxed{0}</mrow>
</md>.
We conclude that <m>z=-1+i</m> is a GCD of <m>2</m> and <m>1+3i</m>. Furthermore, we have
<md>
    <mrow>(-1+i) \amp =-(1+i)2+(1+3i)</mrow>
</md>.
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<corollary xml:id="cor_bezout_gauss">
    <title>Bezout's theorem for <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            For any two elements <m>\alpha, \beta\in \Z[i]</m>, one of which is nonzero, there is a GCD <m>\delta\in \Z[i]</m>. Furthermore, we can write 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\delta \amp =\gamma \alpha+\omega \beta</mrow> 
            </md> 
            for elements <m>\gamma, \omega\in \Z[i]</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>
<corollary xml:id="cor_rel_prime_divis">
    <title>Relatively prime factors</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Assume <m>\alpha,\beta</m> are relatively prime elements of <m>\Z[i]</m>. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\alpha\mid \beta\gamma</m>, then <m>\alpha\mid \gamma</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\alpha\mid \gamma</m> and <m>\beta\mid \gamma</m>, then <m>\alpha\beta\mid \gamma</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Since <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are relatively prime, we can write <m>1=\delta \alpha+\omega\beta</m> some <m>\delta, \omega\in R</m>. We will make use of this expression in both parts below. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Assume that <m>\alpha\mid \beta\gamma</m> for some <m>\gamma in R</m>. By definition this means <m>\beta\gamma=\epsilon \alpha</m> for some <m>\epsilon\in R</m>. It follows that 
                        <md number="yes">
                            <mrow>\gamma \amp =\gamma (\delta\alpha+\omega\beta)</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (\gamma\delta)\alpha+\omega \ beta\gamma</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = (\gamma\delta+\omega\epsilon)\alpha</mrow>
                        </md>,
                        and thus that <m>\alpha\mid \gamma</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       Assume that <m>\alpha\mid \gamma</m> and <m>\beta\mid \gamma</m> for some <m>\gamma in R</m>. By definition, this means <m>\gamma=\epsilon \alpha</m> and <m>\gamma=\phi \beta</m> for some <m>\epsilon, \phi\in R</m>. From <m>1=\delta\alpha+\omega\beta</m> it now follows that 
                       <md>
                        <mrow>\gamma \amp =\gamma\delta\alpha+\gamma\omega\beta</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = (\delta\phi)\alpha\beta+(\gamma\epsilon)\alpha\beta</mrow>
                       </md>,
                       and we see that <m>\alpha\beta\mid \gamma</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
</corollary>


</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_primes_irreducibles">
<title>Primes and irreducibles in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<definition xml:id="d_prime_irreducible">
<title>Primes and irreducibles</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a subring of <m>\C</m>, and let <m>\alpha</m> be a nonzero non-unit of <m>R</m>: <ie/>, <m>\alpha\in R-(R^*\cup \{0\})</m>.
<ul>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha</m> is <term>irreducible</term> if <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m> implies <m>\beta\in R^*</m> <m>\gamma\in R^*</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha</m> is <term>prime</term> if <m>\alpha\mid \beta\gamma</m> implies <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m> or <m>\alpha\mid \gamma</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<remark>
    <title>Disentangling primes and irreducibles</title>
    <p>
        The two separate definitions above might come as a surprise to you, since in the context of <m>\Z</m> the two are equivalent! For a general subring <m>R\subseteq \C</m>, however, this is not the case. Although it is the case that all prime elements are irreducible, there are rings with irreducible elements that are not prime. Thankfully for us, in <m>\Z[i]</m> as in <m>\Z</m>, the two notions are equivalent. 
    </p>
</remark>
<theorem xml:id="th_prime_irr">
<title>Prime equivalent to irreducible in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\pi\in \Z[i]</m> be a nonzero non-unit. The following statements are equivalent. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
        <m>\pi</m> is prime.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\pi</m> is irreducible. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    The easier implication is (1)<m>\implies</m>(2); and indeed this implication holds for <em>any</em> subring <m>R\subseteq \C</m>.  Assume <m>\pi</m> is prime. If <m>\pi=\alpha\beta</m>, then in particular <m>\pi\mid \alpha\beta</m>. Since <m>\pi</m> is prime, we have <m>\pi\mid \alpha</m> or <m>\pi\mid \beta</m>. If <m>\pi\mid \alpha</m>, then we have <m>\alpha=\pi\gamma</m> for some <m>\gamma\in \Z[i]</m>, and hence 
    <md>
        \pi=\alpha\beta=\pi\gamma\beta
    </md>.
    Since <m>\pi</m> is nonzero, it has a multiplicative inverse in <m>\C</m>, allowing us to cancel and conclude <m>1=\gamma\beta</m>. Since <m>\gamma\in \Z[i]</m>, we conclude that <m>\beta\in (\Z[i])^*</m>. The case where <m>\pi\mid \beta</m> is exactly similar. 
</p>
<p>
    The implication (2)<m>\implies</m>(1) is <em>not true</em> for a general subring <m>R\subseteq \C</m>. As you will see, the key property of <m>\Z[i]</m> we use is the existence of GCDs and Bezout's theorem. Assume <m>\pi</m> is irreducible, and that <m>\pi\mid \alpha\beta</m> for <m>\alpha,\beta\in \Z[i]</m>. We wish to show that <m>\pi\mid \alpha</m> or <m>\pi\mid \beta</m>. To this end, assume that <m>\pi\nmid \alpha</m>. We claim that <m>\pi</m> and <m>\alpha</m> are relatively prime in this case. Indeed, since <m>\pi</m> is irreducible, its only divisors are units and associates of itself. It follows that a common divisor of <m>\pi</m> and <m>\alpha</m> would be a unit or an associate of <m>\pi</m>. But since <m>\pi\nmid \alpha</m>, no associate of <m>\pi</m> divides <m>\alpha</m>. We conclude that the only common divisors of <m>\pi</m> and <m>\alpha</m> are units, and hence that the two are are relatively prime. From <xref ref="cor_rel_prime_divis"/> we conclude that <m>\pi\mid \beta</m>, as desired. 
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<remark>
<title>Prime/irreducible</title>
<p>
From here on out, we are justified in using the terms <q>prime</q> and <q>irreducible</q> interchangeably when working in <m>\Z[i]</m>. For the sheer sake of brevity, as well as its familiar ring, we will prefer the term <q>prime</q>. However, when emphasizing the fact the two notions in <xref ref="d_prime_irreducible"/> are equivalent in this setting, we will sometimes write <q>prime/irreducible</q>. 
</p>
</remark>
<p>
    We are nearly prepared to prove a prime factorization theorem for <m>\Z[i]</m> that is a straightforward generalization of the corresponding result for <m>\Z</m>. The existence of prime factorizations will proceed by induction on the Gaussian norm of an element, and for the base case, we will need the following useful result.
</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop_primes_norm">
    <title>Primes, norms, and conjugates</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\pi\in \Z[i]</m> be a nonzero non-unit. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\pi</m> is prime if and only if <m>\overline{\pi}</m> is prime if and only if <m>u\pi</m> is prime for any unit <m>u\in \Z[i]^*</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>N(\pi)=p</m> for <m>p</m> a prime integer, then <m>\pi</m> is prime in <m>\Z[i]</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>\pi</m> is prime in <m>\Z[i]</m>, then <m>N(\pi)\in \{p,p^2\}</m>, where <m>p</m> is a prime integer. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Proof by delegation. (In other words, this is left to you!) The first equivalence follows easily from the fact that <m>\overline{\alpha\beta}=\overline{\alpha}\overline{\beta}</m>. The second follows from the fact that units <m>u</m> can be cancelled multiplicatively in equations involving Gaussian integers. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Assume <m>N(\pi)=p</m> where <m>p</m> is a prime integer. We will show <m>\pi</m> is irreducible, hence prime. Given <m>\alpha,\beta\in \Z[i]</m>, we have 
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\pi=\alpha\beta \amp \implies p=N(\pi)=N(\alpha)N(\beta)</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \implies \{N(\alpha),N(\beta)\}=\{1,p\} \amp (p \text{ prime})</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \implies N(\alpha)=1 \text{ or } N(\beta)=1</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp \implies \alpha\in \Z[i]^* \text{ or } \beta\in \Z[i]^*</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        Thus <m>\pi</m> is irreducible/prime, as claimed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Assume <m>\pi</m> is prime/irreducible. Write <m>a=N(\pi)</m>, where <m>a</m> is an integer and <m>a&gt; 1</m> (since <m>\pi</m> is not unit). By prime factorization, we can write <m>a=\prod_{i=1}^r p_i</m> for primes <m>p_i</m>. Since <m>\pi\mid a</m> in <m>\Z[i]</m>, it divides <m>p_i</m> for some <m>i</m>. Call <m>p=p_i</m>. Since <m>\pi\mid p</m>, we have 
                        <m>p=\pi\alpha</m> for some <m>\alpha\in \Z[i]</m>. Taking conjugates, we have
                        <md>
                            <mrow>p\amp=\overline{p}=\overline{\pi}\overline{\alpha} \amp </mrow>
                        </md>.
                        But then 
                        <md>
                            <mrow>p^2 \amp =pp</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =\pi\overline{\pi}\alpha\overline{\alpha}</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = N(\pi)N(\alpha)</mrow>
                        </md>.
                        Since <m>p</m> is prime the only factors of <m>p^2</m> are <m>1,p,p^2</m>. Since <m>N(\pi)\ne 1</m>, we conclude that <m>N(\pi)\in\{p,p^2\}</m>, as claimed. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>
<example xml:id="eg_gauss_primes">
<title>Gaussian primes</title>
<statement>
<p>
For each Gaussian integer <m>\alpha</m> verify directly whether it is prime or not, and compare your answer with <m>N(\alpha)</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=1+i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=1-i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=3</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=-1+3i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
Note that <m>N(1+i)=N(1-i)=2</m>, which implies (indirectly) that these elements are both prime. To verify this directly, it is easiest to show that <m>\alpha</m> in this case is irreducible, and this is done using a norm argument identical to the one used in the proof of <xref ref="prop_primes_norm"/>. Note that <m>1-i=\overline{1+i}</m>, and thus the primality of either element implies the primality of the other. Interestingly, we also have <m>1-i=(-i)(1+i)</m>, so these two primes are in fact associates of each other. More on that later. Lastly, the nontrivial factorization <m>2=(1+i)(1-i)</m> shows that <m>2</m>, though prime in <m>\Z</m>, is not prime in <m>\Z[i]</m>.
</p>
<p>
    We claim <m>3</m> is prime in <m>\Z[i]</m>. If <m>3=\alpha\beta</m>, then <m>9=N(3)=N(\alpha)N(\beta)</m>. Since the divisors of <m>9</m> are <m>1,3,9</m>, we see that either <m>\{N(\alpha),N(\beta)\}=\{3\}</m>, or <m>\{N(\alpha), N(\beta)\}=\{1,9\}</m>. The first option is impossible, as there are no integers <m>a,b\in \Z</m> satisfying <m>3=a^2+b^2</m>. The latter implies that <m>\alpha</m> is a unit or <m>\beta</m> is a unit, as desired. Note in this case that <m>3</m> is prime in <m>\Z[i]</m>, but its norm <m>N(3)=9</m> is not prime. It is, however, equal to the square of a prime, as predicted by <xref ref="prop_primes_norm"/>.
</p>
<p>
    We first compute <m>N(\alpha)=1+9=10</m>. Since <m>10</m> is not <m>p</m> or <m>p^2</m> for any prime integer <m>p</m>, we must have <m>\alpha</m> not prime/irreducible. To verify this directly, note that if <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m> is a nontrivial factorization, then <m>\{N(\beta),N(\gamma)\}=\{2,5\}</m>. This tells us to look for factors of <m>\alpha</m> with norm <m>2</m> and <m>5</m>, which leads us to the nontrivial factorization <m>-1+3i=(1+i)(1+2i)</m>. 
</p>

</solution>
</example>
<p>
    We are ready at last for our prime factorization theorem for <m>\Z[i]</m>. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_unique_factorization_gauss">
<title>Prime factorization in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\alpha\in \Z[i]</m> be a nonzero non-unit element. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <title>Prime factorization</title>
        <p>
            There are prime/irreducible elements <m>\pi_1,\pi_2,\dots, \pi_r</m> of <m>\Z[i]</m> satisfying 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\alpha \amp =\pi_1\pi_2\cdots \pi_r</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Uniqueness of factorization</title>
        <p>
            If we have 
            <md>
                \alpha=\pi_1\pi_2\cdots \pi_r=\pi_1'\pi_2'\cdots \pi_s'
            </md>,
            with <m>\pi_i</m> and <m>\pi_j'</m> prime/irreducible for all <m>i</m> and <m>j</m>, then <m>r=s</m>, and after a reordering, for all <m>i</m> we have <m>\pi_i'=u_i\pi_i</m> for some unit <m>u_i\in (\Z[i])^*=\{1,-1,i,-i\}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            In particular, the number of irreducible factors in an irreducible factorization of <m>\alpha</m> is unique, and the irreducible factors are unique up to multiplication by a unit (<ie/>, up to associates). 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                The proof is by strong induction on $N(\alpha)$, the base case being <m>N(\alpha)=2</m>. (We cannot have <m>N(\alpha)\in \{0,1\}</m>, since <m>\alpha</m> by assumption is a nonzero non-unit.)  If $N(\alpha)=2$, then <m>\alpha</m> is itself prime by <xref ref="prop_primes_norm"/>, and we are done. 
            </p>
            <p>
                For the strong induction step, we assume the result is true for all Gaussian integers with norm in <m>\{2,3,\dots, n-1\}</m>. Assume <m>N(\alpha)=n</m>. If <m>\alpha</m> is prime/irreducible, we are done. Otherwise, we can write <m>\alpha=\beta\gamma</m> for some non-units <m>\beta,\gamma\in \Z[i]</m>. Since <m>n=N(\alpha)=N(\beta)N(\gamma)</m>, and since <m>N(\beta),N(\gamma)&gt; 1</m>, we conclude that <m>\{N(\beta),N(\gamma)\}\subseteq \{2,3,\dots, n-1\}</m>. By induction we have 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\beta \amp= \pi_1\pi_2\cdots \pi_r \amp \gamma \amp= \pi_1'\pi_2'\cdots \pi_s' </mrow>
                </md>
                for primes <m>\pi_i, \pi_j'</m>. But then 
                <md>
                    \alpha=\beta\gamma=\pi_1\cdots \pi_r\pi_1'\cdots \pi_s'
                </md>
                is a prime factorization of <m>\alpha</m>, as desired.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                The uniqueness claim is proved by induction on the minimal length <m>r</m> of a prime factorization. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Base step: <m>r=1</m>. In this case we have <m>\alpha</m> itself prime/irreducible. Suppose <m>\alpha=\prod_{i=1}^s\pi_i</m> is another prime factorization. If <m>s&gt; 1</m>, then we would be able to write <m>\alpha=\pi_1 \cdot \beta</m>, where <m>\pi</m> and <m>\beta=\prod_{i=2}^s\pi_i</m> are both non-units, contradicting the irreducibility of <m>\alpha</m>. Thus <m>s=1</m>, and we have <m>\alpha=\pi_1</m>. This proves the uniqueness claim for the case <m>r=1</m> when <m>\alpha</m> is itself prime. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Induction step: we assume that for any <m>\beta\in \Z[i]</m> with a prime factorization of minimal length <m>r\geq 1</m>, the factorization is unique in the manner described. Suppose <m>\alpha</m> has a prime factorization of minimal length <m>r+1</m> of the form 
                <md>
                    \alpha=\prod_{i=1}^{r+1}\pi_i
                </md>
                and suppose <m>\alpha=\prod_{i=1}^{s} \pi_i'</m> is another prime factorization. Since <m>r</m> is minimal, we must have <m>s\geq r</m>. Since <m>\pi_1\mid \alpha=\prod_{i=1}^s\pi_i'</m>, we must have <m>\pi_1\mid \pi_{i_0}'</m> for some <m>1\leq i_{0}\leq s</m>. After a re-ordering, we may assume <m>i_0=1</m>. We then have <m>\pi_{1}'=u_1\pi_1</m> for some unit <m>u\in \Z[i]^*</m>. This allows us to cancel <m>\pi_1</m> from both sides of the equation, yielding 
                <md>
                    \beta=\prod_{i=2}^{r+1}\pi_i=\prod_{i=2}^s\pi_i'
                </md>.
                Since <m>\beta</m> has a prime factorization of minimal length (at most) <m>r</m>, induction applies.It follows that <m>r=s-1</m>, and after a reordering, <m>\pi_i'=u_i\pi_i</m> for some unit <m>u_i\in \Z[i]^*</m> for all <m>i\geq 2</m>. But then we have <m>r+1=s</m> and <m>\pi_i'=u_i\pi_i</m> for all <m>1\leq i\leq r+1</m>, as desired.  
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    As with factorization in <m>\Z</m>, from a prime factorization of an element <m>\alpha</m>, we can produce a <em>prime power</em> factorization by grouping together <q>like</q> primes, which in this case means primes that are associate. For example, from the prime factorization 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>6 \amp = (1+i)(1-i)3</mrow>
    </md>,
    observing that <m>1-i=(-i)(1+i)</m>, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>6 \amp =(-i)(1+i)^2 3</mrow>
    </md>,
    expressing <m>6</m> as a product of a unit and powers of two <em>non-associate primes</em>. The corollary below gives the general result. The proof is very similar to the analogous result for integers and is left to the reader. 
</p>
<corollary xml:id="cor_prime_power_fact_gauss">
    <title>Prime power factorization in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\alpha</m> be a nonzero non-unit element of <m>\Z[i]</m>. 
            <ol>
                
                <li>
                    <title>Prime power factorization</title>
                    <p>
                      There are pairwise non-associate prime/irreducible elements <m>\pi_1,\pi_2,\dots, \pi_r\in \Z[i]</m>,positive integers <m>n_1,n_2,\dots, n_r</m>, and a unit <m>u\in \Z[i]^*</m> such that 
                      <md number="yes">
                        <mrow>\alpha \amp =u\prod_{i=1}^r\pi_i^{n_i}</mrow>
                      </md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Uniqueness of factorization</title>

                    <p>
                        If 
                        <md number="yes">
                            <mrow>\alpha\amp= u'\prod_{i=1}^s(\pi_i')^{m_i} </mrow>
                        </md>
                        is another such factorization into powers of pairwise nonassociate primes <m>\pi_i'</m>, then <m>r=s</m>, and after a reordering, <m>\pi_i'</m> is associate to <m>\pi_i</m> and <m>n_i=m_i</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>
</subsection>
    

</section>